<div id="review_202849361" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/202849361" />
    <a title="D.H. Nevins" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5810087-d-h-nevins"><img alt="D.H. Nevins" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442603278p2/5810087.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/202849361?book_show_action=true">Aug 27, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="D.H. Nevins" class="user" itemprop="url" name="D.H. Nevins" href="/user/show/5810087-d-h-nevins">D.H. Nevins</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer202849361" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10333843891204981095">This is a poignant story about finding compassion and understanding in an existence that, at first glance, appears to be devoid of both. The two girls in the book, Ann Marie and Jolene—in fact, the entire Adler family—are painted in such tangible, vivid colours, I connected with them instantly. Even when I wasn’t reading the book, I found the characters frequently tangled in my thoughts—wondering what they should do; saddened by their plights, and thinking about their futures. Even the story’s a</span>
  <span id="freeText10333843891204981095" style="display:none">This is a poignant story about finding compassion and understanding in an existence that, at first glance, appears to be devoid of both. The two girls in the book, Ann Marie and Jolene—in fact, the entire Adler family—are painted in such tangible, vivid colours, I connected with them instantly. Even when I wasn’t reading the book, I found the characters frequently tangled in my thoughts—wondering what they should do; saddened by their plights, and thinking about their futures. Even the story’s antagonists, who I <i>wanted</i> to hate, were so miserably fragile and so utterly human in their deficiencies, that my heart broke for them. <br /><br />Ms. Johnson crafted a gripping, compelling tale that instantly immersed me into her characters’ brutal lives right from the first page. In fact, I was so absorbed, I read the entire first chapter while standing in the centre of my living room. I simply meant to glance at the book’s opening, and before I knew it, I had inhaled the whole chapter. Expect <i>Small as a Mustard Seed</i> to take you on an emotional journey that you’ll never forget.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10333843891204981095" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


