    <a title="Tom Harris" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7947530-tom-harris"><img alt="Tom Harris" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1500721509p2/7947530.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/299499331?book_show_action=true">Mar 23, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tom Harris" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tom Harris" href="/user/show/7947530-tom-harris">Tom Harris</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/12086697-small-as-a-mustard-seed">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer299499331" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12533191067737572487">Charting a journey through adolescence in Stanhope, Ohio, from 1965 to 1973 and beyond, this is a moving tale about the brutality and disintegration of the human condition and having the courage and faith to survive it.<br/><br/>Anne-Marie and her sister, Jolene, are constantly terrified of their father, Frank, a war veteran with schizophrenia who suffers from flashbacks and paranoia induced by his time serving in Korea. The two girls escape into their imagination as they deal with parental abuse when mis</span>
  <span id="freeText12533191067737572487" style="display:none">Charting a journey through adolescence in Stanhope, Ohio, from 1965 to 1973 and beyond, this is a moving tale about the brutality and disintegration of the human condition and having the courage and faith to survive it.<br /><br />Anne-Marie and her sister, Jolene, are constantly terrified of their father, Frank, a war veteran with schizophrenia who suffers from flashbacks and paranoia induced by his time serving in Korea. The two girls escape into their imagination as they deal with parental abuse when mistaken as ghosts from their traumatised father’s past. With their mother, Adele, unable to choose between her husband and the safety of her daughters all the girls have is each other and their faith to help them survive the horrors of the cellar and their father and his worsening condition.<br /><br />Beautifully written, this is a powerful story about the effects of war on family. Johnson delves into the strengths and weaknesses of the human condition and pulls no punches in her harrowing prose. Ultimately, this is a story about strength and faith and holding onto the hope that a better tomorrow awaits us all.<br /><br />A brave and stunning debut by Shelli Johnson, a sensory overload, written with great courage and skill as its beautiful prose leads you by the hand through the harsh reality of a family doing the best it can to survive the impact of a broken mind. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="12533191067737572487" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


