  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/224181162?book_show_action=true">Oct 16, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Patricia Paris" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Patricia Paris" href="/user/show/6497317-patricia-paris">Patricia Paris</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/12086697-small-as-a-mustard-seed">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer224181162" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15547117697913740777">Shelly Johnson has created a masterpiece in Small As A Mustard Seed. From page one, I was pulled into this grippingly emoional story of the Adler family. Johnson is a word artist, crafting beautifully written scenes that come to life through vivid description and masterful character development. <br/>This is a story of complex relationships and fractured lives. Johnson makes you feel every ounce of the, anger, confusion, fear and desperation sisters Anne Marie and Jolene experience toward their paren</span>
  <span id="freeText15547117697913740777" style="display:none">Shelly Johnson has created a masterpiece in Small As A Mustard Seed. From page one, I was pulled into this grippingly emoional story of the Adler family. Johnson is a word artist, crafting beautifully written scenes that come to life through vivid description and masterful character development. <br />This is a story of complex relationships and fractured lives. Johnson makes you feel every ounce of the, anger, confusion, fear and desperation sisters Anne Marie and Jolene experience toward their parents. Their mother's emotional desertion and refusal to protect her daughters, and their father's mental illness are the walls of a prison they are helpless to escape. Through it all, the reader is torn, whipped along on a roller coaster of emotion, feeling angry at the girl's parents, and sorry for them at the same time. <br />Small As A Mustard Seed is a testament to the human spirit and of how even the tiniest grain of hope can be enough! I will recommend this book highly. </span>
  <a data-text-id="15547117697913740777" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


