<div id="review_283065306" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/283065306" />
    <a title="Sher" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7897465-sher"><img alt="Sher" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1330053130p2/7897465.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/283065306?book_show_action=true">Feb 23, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sher" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sher" href="/user/show/7897465-sher">Sher</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/12086697-small-as-a-mustard-seed">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer283065306" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13777309430916851559">A powerful book regarding deep, deep pain and the process/ability for forgiveness. Characters developed so believably one finds oneself wearing their clothes and feeling their pain/trauma/quandary. Life isn&apos;t fair, and the ramifications of an unfair life leaves scars too thick to ever fully disappear, yet, with time and permission, can fade enough to allow movement forward to forgiveness. A book worth sharing and gifting.</span>
  <span id="freeText13777309430916851559" style="display:none">A powerful book regarding deep, deep pain and the process/ability for forgiveness. Characters developed so believably one finds oneself wearing their clothes and feeling their pain/trauma/quandary. Life isn't fair, and the ramifications of an unfair life leaves scars too thick to ever fully disappear, yet, with time and permission, can fade enough to allow movement forward to forgiveness. A book worth sharing and gifting.</span>
