    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_361143280" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/361143280" />
    <a title="John Paul Davis" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8609189-john-paul-davis"><img alt="John Paul Davis" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1636484463p2/8609189.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/361143280?book_show_action=true">Jul 04, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="John Paul Davis" class="user" itemprop="url" name="John Paul Davis" href="/user/show/8609189-john-paul-davis">John Paul Davis</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/12086697-small-as-a-mustard-seed">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer361143280" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2037922977227909046">I think I need to start this review by highlighting that there is nothing I can possibly say that will even come close to doing this justice. Only by experiencing this novel first hand can one even begin to understand.<br/><br/>In essence, Small as a Mustard Seed is a 1st person narrative about a small girl growing up in a complicated middle American household in the 60s and 70s. The story is told through the eyes of young Ann-Marie Adler, older sister of artistically talented Jolene and daughter of Frank</span>
  <span id="freeText2037922977227909046" style="display:none">I think I need to start this review by highlighting that there is nothing I can possibly say that will even come close to doing this justice. Only by experiencing this novel first hand can one even begin to understand.<br /><br />In essence, Small as a Mustard Seed is a 1st person narrative about a small girl growing up in a complicated middle American household in the 60s and 70s. The story is told through the eyes of young Ann-Marie Adler, older sister of artistically talented Jolene and daughter of Frank and Adele. Every chapter is in essence a year in the life of her strained upbringing as she and her sister struggle to exist side by side with her father, a hardened war veteran whose mental state is in a dangerous state of decline, and her mother's ignorance of her husband's actions, potentially compromising her children's safety.<br /><br />The book is a triumph on many levels. Johnson's ability to capture the spirit and settings of 5 decades ago really added to the atmosphere of the book. Her dialogue and descriptions were also very effective in this way. The subject matter is enthralling and almost certainly required large amounts of research. Again, the author has done an incredible job constructing, and controlling, the theme of her book.<br /><br />But for me the out and out stars are the characters. Johnson's ability to build such a close relationship with her characters and allow the same connection with her readers is nothing short of exemplary. Not only is every action, thought, and sentence perfectly captured by Johnson's flowing literature, but her ability to identify Ann-Maria, and her situation, so closely with the sympathies of her audiences makes it impossible to read this and not feel completely taken in. Small as a Mustard Seed is a story of hope and dreams and tragedy. And I for one experienced everyone with her!<br /><br />I really hope it gets the recognition it deserves.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2037922977227909046" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


